[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(9) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Cried unto the Lord.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—“In the time of their trouble, when they cried unto Thee, Thou heardest them from heaven; and according to Thy manifold mercies Thou gavest them saviours” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 9:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). “Then they cried unto the Lord in their trouble, and He saved them out of their distresses” (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 107:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; see, too, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 26:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 78:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 106:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A deliverer.—Heb., moshia; LXX., “a saviour.” (Comp. Luke 1:69; Acts 13:23.) The same word as is used for the judges in Hebrews 9:27.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "A deliverer.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Heb., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "moshia; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "LXX., “a saviour.” (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 1:69",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 13:23",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) The same word as is used for the judges in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Hebrews 9:27",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Othniel.—The name means “lion of God.” St. Jerome makes it mean “my time of God,” and spells it Athaniel",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Othniel.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The name means “lion of God.” St. Jerome makes it mean “my time of God,” and spells it Athaniel",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The son of Kenaz.—(See Judges 1:13.) Josephus, to escape the apparent improbability of a brother of Caleb being young enough to marry Caleb’s daughter, when Caleb was past eighty-five, calls him “a person of the tribe of Judah.” He rightly regards the events of Judges 17-21 as preceding the judgeship of Othniel; but they can hardly have happened during the oppression of Cushan-Rishathaim.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The son of Kenaz.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—(See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Judges 1:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".) Josephus, to escape the apparent improbability of a brother of Caleb being young enough to marry Caleb’s daughter, when Caleb was past eighty-five, calls him “a person of the tribe of Judah.” He rightly regards the events of Judges 17-21 as preceding the judgeship of Othniel; but they can hardly have happened during the oppression of Cushan-Rishathaim.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jdg 3:9-10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 3:9-10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "When the children of Israel cried unto the Lord — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "When they returned to him in repentance, acknowledged him to be their only Protector and Saviour, and prayed fervently for pardon and deliverance; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the Lord raised up a deliverer ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Qualified a person for, and called him to, the great work of delivering them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The Spirit of the Lord came upon him — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "With extraordinary influence, endowing him with singular wisdom and courage, and stirring him up to this great undertaking. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Judged Israel — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is, pleaded and avenged the cause of Israel against their oppressors. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And went out to war — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The sacred historian gives us no further account of this war than that Othniel obtained a victory over the king of Mesopotamia, and a peace which lasted forty years. This victory and deliverance of Israel, it seems, happened about thirty-eight years after the death of Joshua.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3:8-11 The first judge was Othniel: even in Joshua's time Othniel began to be famous. Soon after Israel's settlement in Canaan their purity began to be corrupted, and their peace disturbed. But affliction makes those cry to God who before would scarcely speak to him. God returned in mercy to them for their deliverance. The Spirit of the Lord came upon Othniel. The Spirit of wisdom and courage to qualify him for the service, and the Spirit of power to excite him to it. He first judged Israel, reproved and reformed them, and then went to war. Let sin at home be conquered, that worst of enemies, then enemies abroad will be more easily dealt with. Thus let Christ be our Judge and Lawgiver, then he will save us.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
